<H2><A title=3D"Permanent link to this item"=20
href=3D"http://textism.com/2008/04/07/renderance">Renderance</A></H2>
<H3><SPAN class=3Doutleft>7 Apr 2008, 11am</SPAN></H3>
<P><SPAN class=3Doutright><IMG height=3D70 alt=3D"Safari kerning"=20
src=3D"http://textism.com/img/safarikern.png" width=3D85><BR>Safari: =
right face, bad=20
kern</SPAN></P>
<P>Here=E2=80=99s a seemingly insurmountable, earth-in-the-balance =
problem I could use=20
some help with. Safari evidently has no trouble rendering a standard,=20
Apple-installed font face like Helvetica Neue Light when it=E2=80=99s =
named in <SPAN=20
class=3Dcaps>CSS</SPAN> by its PostScript handle =
=E2=80=98HelveticaNeue-Light=E2=80=99, but it=20
ignores the font=E2=80=99s metrics and kerns letter pairs like David =
Carson on a bad=20
day. I=E2=80=99d thought <A title=3D"Wikipedia article on Apple's Core =
Text technology"=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Core_Text">Core Text</A> was a =
system-wide=20
thing these days, but then I=E2=80=99ve been out of it for awhile.</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Doutright><IMG height=3D70 alt=3D"Firefox kerning"=20
src=3D"http://textism.com/img/firefoxkern.png" width=3D85><BR>Firefox: =
wrong face,=20
decent kern</SPAN></P>
<P>Firefox and other mozilla browsers, on the other hand, =
<EM>won=E2=80=99t</EM> render=20
a standard, Apple-installed font like Helvetica Neue Light, cascading =
past it to=20
the plain Roman, however the kerning seems to be respected.</P>
<P>I=E2=80=99ve tried using <A title=3D"A List Apart article on =
@font-face"=20
href=3D"http://www.alistapart.com/articles/cssatten/">@font-face</A> =
rules to=20
refer to a TrueType file of the font, but then it just gets weirder: =
Safari=20
loads it, but the metrics are even more wonky. Firefox (as of the 3.0b5 =
I=E2=80=99m=20
using) won=E2=80=99t load the .ttf file at all.</P>
<P>As Fielding Goodney=C2=B9 <SPAN class=3Doutright>=C2=B9Martin Amis,=20
<CITE>Money</CITE></SPAN>would have it, =E2=80=98I hate it when I =
can=E2=80=99t <EM>figure</EM>=20
things=E2=80=99. Any browser geeks out there who can shed some light on =
this, or suggest=20
workarounds? (Other than doing pictures of words that is, not keen on =
that.)=20
Dean at this domain. Thanks in advance.</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Dcaps>UPDATE</SPAN> &nbsp;<A =
href=3D"http://blog.kno.at/">Christian=20
Knoflach</A> points out that Firefox 2, unlike Firefox 3=20
beta,&nbsp;<EM>will</EM> render any system font as long as you reference =
its=20
screen name, e.g., =E2=80=9CHelvetica Neue Light=E2=80=9D, but FF2 still =
has Safari=E2=80=99s bad=20
letterspacing problem. Here=E2=80=99s hoping the release version of =
Firefox 3 will solve=20
both issues, and all will be good and right for the seventeen of us in =
the world=20
who care about this sort of malarkey.</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Dcaps>UPDATE</SPAN> 2 &nbsp;Evidently kerning in Safari =
has been=20
an <A href=3D"http://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=3D6136">issue of =
complaint</A>=20
for some time (thx Daniele).&nbsp;</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Dcaps>UPDATE</SPAN> <SPAN class=3Dcaps>THE</SPAN> <SPAN=20
class=3Dcaps>LAST&nbsp;</SPAN> <A href=3D"http://l-c-n.com/">Philippe=20
Wittenbergh</A> (and a few others I stupidly brushed off earlier for =
suggesting=20
font-weight was the way to do it) says that FF3 beta&nbsp;<EM>does</EM> =
know=20
what it=E2=80=99s doing when it comes to rendering different weights =
(and not simply=20
shaving off pixels as older browsers have done):</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>What Gecko 1.9 (Firefox 3) does is correct by the logic of <SPAN=20
  class=3Dcaps>CSS</SPAN>.</P>
  <P>You select a font =E2=80=98family=E2=80=99 (Helvetica Neue), and =
then a specific face (by=20
  font-weight in this case).</P>
  <P>p {font-family: =E2=80=98Helvetica Neue=E2=80=99, sans-serif; =
font-weight: 300;}</P>
  <P>This will work correctly in Gecko and, when it comes out, Safari =
3.2 (full=20
  support for various font-weights was only checked in in Webkit last =
Friday,=20
  2008.04.04).</P>
  <P>Add =E2=80=98HelveticaNeue-Light=E2=80=99 for backwards =
compatibility with older=20
  browsers.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>So Safari in the near future, and looky here.&nbsp;Firefox 3.0b5, you =

beautiful bastard you:</P>
<P><IMG height=3D74 alt=3D"Firefox 3b5 light helv neue kerning"=20
src=3D"http://textism.com/img/ff3b5kerning.png" width=3D213></P>
<P>Still looks like complete pants on Windows, but no surprises there. =
Thanks to=20
all for the tips.</P></DIV></BODY></HTML>

